===Etymology===
From {{etyl|gem-pro|ang}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*wurdą}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|ang}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*werdʰo-||word}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|ang}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*wer-||speak}}; cognate with Old Frisian {{term|word|lang=ofs}}, Old Saxon {{term|word|lang=osx}}, Old Dutch {{term|wort|lang=odt}} (Dutch {{term|woord|lang=nl}}), Old High German {{term|wort|lang=goh}} (German {{term|Wort|lang=de}}), Old Norse {{term|orð|lang=non}} (Icelandic {{term|orð|lang=is}}, Swedish {{term|ord|lang=sv}}), Gothic {{term|sc=Goth|𐍅𐌰𐌿𐍂𐌳|tr=waurd|lang=got}}. The Proto-Indo-European root is also the source of Latin {{term|verbum|lang=la}}, Lithuanian {{term|vardas|lang=lt}}, and, more distantly, of Ancient Greek {{term|εἴρω||I say|tr=eirō|lang=grc}} and Old Slavonic {{term|||to swear|tr=rotiti sę|lang=cu}} (Russian {{term|ротиться|tr=rotit’sja||to vow|lang=ru}}).

