===Etymology 3===
From an alteration of earlier {{term|poun|lang=en}}, {{term|pown|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|pounen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term/t|ang|pūnian||to pound, beat, bray, bruise, crush}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*pūnōną||to break to pieces, pulverise}}. Related to {{etyl|stq|-}} {{term|Pün||debris, fragments|lang=stq}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|puin||debris, fragments, rubbish|lang=nl}}, {{etyl|nds|-}} {{term|pun||fragments|lang=nds}}. Perhaps influenced by '''Etymology 2''' {{etyl|enm|-}} {{term/t|enm|*pound}}, {{term|pond|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|-}} {{term/t|ang|*pund}}, {{term|pynd|lang=ang}}, in relation to the hollow [[mortar]] for pounding with the [[pestle]].

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|poun}}, {{l|en|pown}} {{qualifier|obsolete or dialectal}}

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To strike hard, usually repeatedly.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[crush]] to pieces; to [[pulverize]].
# {{context|transitive|slang|lang=en}} To eat or drink very quickly.
#: ''You really '''pounded''' that beer!''
# {{context|transitive|baseball|slang|lang=en}} To [[pitch]] consistently to a certain location.
#: ''The pitcher has been '''pounding''' the outside corner all night.''
# {{context|intransitive|of a body part, generally heart, blood, or head|lang=en}} To [[beat]] strongly or [[throb]].
#: ''As I tiptoed past the sleeping dog, my heart was '''pounding''' but I remained silent.''
#: ''My head was '''pounding'''.''
# {{context|transitive|slang|lang=en}} To [[penetrate]] [[sexual]]ly, with [[vigour]].
#: ''I was '''pounding''' her all night!''
# To advance heavily with measured steps.
#* '''1899''', Joseph Conrad, ''[[s:Heart of Darkness|Heart of Darkness]]'', [[s:Heart of Darkness/Section I|section 1]]
#*: We '''pounded''' along, stopped, landed soldiers; went on, landed custom–house clerks to levy toll in what looked like a God–forsaken wilderness, with a tin shed and a flag–pole lost in it; landed more soldiers—to take care of the custom–house clerks, presumably.
# {{context|engineering|lang=en}} To make a [[jarring]] [[noise]], as when running.
#: ''The engine '''pounds'''.''

